        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Merc. Liby. Jan. 16&#44; 1883.  Tuesday.<lb/>
                Rev. Dr. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I find in a pa<lb/>per this statement&#58; &#34;The Rabbis of<lb/> the Seminary at Breslau say&#58; &#39;Un&#45;<lb/>fermented <hi rend="underline">must</hi> is not regarded as<lb/> wine&#44; and would not suffice for<lb/> the <sic>fulfilment</sic> of the duty to drink<lb/> wine on the Passover Eve.&#34;  Is this<lb/> a correct statement&#63;  Would the use<lb/> of fresh grape&#45;juice be regarded<lb/> by your ministers as a departure<lb/> from the instructions of your stand&#45;<lb/>ards&#63;  Please to inform me.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My &#36;25&#45;&#45; offer in the Boston<lb/> paper&#44; in regard to the language<lb/> attributed to Rev. S. M. Isaacs&#44; did<lb/> not secure any reply&#33;  The son&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Dr. A. S. Isaacs&#44; pronounced the<lb/> story about his father &#34;apocryphal.&#34;<lb/>  I cannot yet learn when or where<lb/> or to whom&#44; or in what publica&#45;<lb/>tion it is claimed that Mr. Isaacs<lb/> made the declaration.  I shall<lb/> trace the matter as carefully<lb/> as I can.  For myself I do not<lb/> see any probability in the story&#59;<lb/> for Mr. Isaacs must have been<lb/> conversant&#44; in London and in<lb/> New York&#44; with many people<lb/> of his own religious connection<lb/> who were bred in the wine coun<lb/>tries of Europe.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have requested a friend of mine in New York to ask the<lb/> Nat. Temp. Soc. Editors what<lb/> was the original source of this<lb/> story.  They ought not to pub.<lb/>lish&#44; as the language of Mr. Isaacs&#44;<lb/> <hi rend="underline">that which his own son does<lb/> not believe that he ever used</hi>&#44; un&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>less they can sustain themselves by<lb/> ample evidence.  I think it is not<lb/> unlikely that Dr. Patton heard<lb/> Mr. Isaacs say <hi rend="underline">something</hi> on the<lb/> subject&#44; and misunderstood&#44;<lb/> and so mis&#45;reported him.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>It would really seem as if we might know <hi rend="underline">the present</hi> so<lb/> as to have no occasion for dis<lb/>pute about it&#59; although we<lb/> may doubt about <hi rend="underline">the past</hi>&#44;<lb/> and be ignorant of <hi rend="underline">the future</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am respectfully<lb/>
                Yours&#44;<lb/>
                S. C. Brace.<lb/></p>
        </body>
